# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aparon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aparon/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:aparon/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:aparon/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:aparon/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:aparon/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:aparon/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:aparon/alfajor] An ***alfajor*** or ***alajú*** (Spanish pronunciation: [alfaˈxoɾ], plural *alfajores*) is a traditional confection.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Originally from present-day Spain, it is found now in Argentina, Bolivia, Southern Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Southern France, Paraguay, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay, and Venezuela.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The alfajor was born in Iberia during the rule of al-Andalus.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The Spanish alfajor is produced in the form of a small cylinder and is sold either individually or in boxes containing several pieces.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Traditional alfajores in Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn flour joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:aparon/alfajor] More modern "industrial" varieties in Uruguay and Argentina, are coated with dark or white chocolate (many *alfajores* are sold in "black" and "white" versions), or simply covered with powdered sugar.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The word had been introduced into Spanish dictionaries in the 14th century.
[src:aparon/alfajor] A similar sweet called *alaú* is found in the Arabic-Hispanic cookbook Kitab al-Tabikh, by an anonymous author.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The Spanish grammarian Nebrija noted the word for the first time in his Latin-Spanish Dictionary (1495) as: *alfaxor* or *alaxur*.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In the 12th century, Raimundo Martin describes in his book *Vocabulista* another possible etymology of the Hispano-Arabic *fasur*, meaning "nectar".
[src:aparon/alfajor] The publication of historical dictionaries of the Spanish language allows one to document both forms of the original *alajur*, written as *alajú* and *alfajor*.
[src:aparon/alfajor] *Alajur* and multiple geographic variations are sweets made of a paste of almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs and honey.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In the Americas, the word *alfajor* was not known until the 19th century.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In Spain, there are a variety of different recipes for preparing *alfajores*, but the most traditional contain flour, honey, almonds and several spices, such as cinnamon.
[src:aparon/alfajor] *Alfajores* are most commonly sold around Christmas.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The traditional Spanish *alfajor* has been produced in Medina-Sidonia (where it is called an *alajú*) since ancient times, and the recipe has been traditionally handed down from father to son.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In this town, there is an account of Mariano Pardo de Figueroa, writing under the pen name Dr.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Thebussem, wherein he wrote that on 2 July 1487, Enrique de Guzmán, second count of Medina Sidonia, ordered the council and majors of the region to send to Malaga 50 cows, 50 oxen, 200 calves and provision of *alajú* from his city.
[src:aparon/alfajor] On 15 September 2004, protected geographical indication was ratified by the *Consejo de agricultura y pesca de la junta de Andalucía* and published in the *Official Journal of the European Union* as *Alfajor de Medina Sidonia* on 6 March 2007.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The regulations of the Andalusian Ministry of Agriculture allow the use of only pure honey, almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs, sugar, flour and spices, such as aniseed, sesame, cilantro, cloves and cinnamon.
[src:aparon/alfajor] These *alfajores* are meant to be presented in a cylindrical shape, with a minimum weight of 30 grams (1.1 oz) each, and with a minimum size of about 7 centimetres (2.8 in) in length and a diameter of 1.5 centimetres (0.59 in).
[src:aparon/alfajor] Each of them will be protected with a wrapping paper, and the ends made an ornament in a spiral shape with a ribbon out of the same paper.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Once individually wrapped, they may be packaged in wood or cardboard boxes, but never in plastic.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In the province of Cuenca, Spain, where the *alfajor* is called *alajú,* it is made with almond, honey and figs, wrapped in a wafer.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In Puerto Rico, they underwent creolization, lost their almond and gained ground cassava.
[src:aparon/alfajor] They can take varying amounts of sugar and spices.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It is possible that Puerto Rico's most common version of this dessert (the South American version with dulce de leche) reached Puerto Rico from Venezuela, but the opposite is also possible.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Depending on region some add cornstarch, citrus zest, ginger and honey, filled with chocolate, vanilla cream, dulce de leche, fruit paste, or coconut.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The filling can be mixed with almonds, sesame seeds, coconut flakes, or sprinkles.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Traditional "alfajores" in Chile, Argentina,and Uruguay consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn starch joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:aparon/alfajor] These are also known as a *Chilean Oreo*.
[src:aparon/alfajor] One variation is called "*alfajor de nieve*" (snow alfajor) and has a white coating consisting of a mixture of egg whites and sugar.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Most *alfajores* come packaged in aluminium foil.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Alfajores are made in various diameters and are consumed as snacks.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The *alfajor* has been manufactured and consumed since colonial times in the territories that today belong to Argentina.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The filling is usually dulce de leche, although there are many variations.
[src:aparon/alfajor] They can be covered with powder sugar (the traditional ones), glazed sugar (Santafesinos or "de nieve"), grated coconut or chocolate.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Argentina is one of the world's largest consumers of alfajores, both in total numbers and in per capita calculations, consuming more than a billion alfajores a year.
[src:aparon/alfajor] One important Argentine alfajor is the alfajor de Santa Fe or the alfajor santafesino, which has three puff pastry layers adhered to one another with dulce de leche and glazed all over.
[src:aparon/alfajor] This alfajor is closely linked to the history of the city of Santa Fe.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Colonel Néstor Fernández from Santa Fe took it to the Battle of Caseros in 1851.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It became so popular with the army that General Justo José de Urquiza had a weekly shipment of these alfajores delivered to his estancia in San José de Entre Ríos.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The production of Santa Fe alfajores began in 1851 in a shop located on the southwest corner of San Jerónimo and 3 de Febrero streets, a few meters from the Cabildo (where the Santa Fe Government House currently stands).
[src:aparon/alfajor] These alfajores became known throughout the country after the 24 writers of the constitution, who, after living in Santa Fe for six months, took this dessert home as a souvenir.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Today, it is a heritage of the city of Santa Fe and is handcrafted in that city and its surrounding areas.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The nickname "Merengo" gave rise to a brand of alfajores.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The Cordobes alfajor is filled with fruit jellies (generally of quince).
[src:aparon/alfajor] In addition, there is the Rogel, similar to the Santa Fe but bigger (the size of a small cake) and a variety from Tucuman known as a clarita, with two crunchy cookies and filled with a jelly made up of sugar molasses.
[src:aparon/alfajor] In Argentina, alfajores made up of cornflour are very consumed as well (covers made up of maize starch, filled with dulce de leche and grated coconut around the filling).
[src:aparon/alfajor] Mass-production of alfajores traces back to the Atlantic coast of Argentina in the 1950s.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Brands such as Havanna and Balcarce, and as many as 30 others, have been introduced into shops and supermarkets.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Statistics of the year 2021 shows that inhabitants of Argentina consume 6 million alfajores per day.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Two types of alfajores are found in Chile.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The first type of alfajor, similar to the one of corn flour prepared in other countries of Latin America, is prepared over all the territory of Chile, but mainly in the central area of Chile.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It is known as "candy of corn flour" or, more typically, "chilenitos".
[src:aparon/alfajor] The chilenitos are manufactured with corn flour or other types of flour and tend to be simpler and smaller than the other alfajores.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The second type of alfajor, considered the true traditional alfajor of the country and known as "chilean alfajor", is mainly prepared in the southern areas of Chile, generally for the patriotic festivities of September.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It is prepared with two hojarascas (a thin and firm cookie) that, since they are previously baked, acquire a curved form.
[src:aparon/alfajor] They are adhered to each other with dark brown sugar, panela, manjar or with confectioners cream.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Optionally, they can be garnished in the end of the filling with grated coconut as it is the case of the alfajores filled with manjar or with ground nuts.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Alfajores made their arrival to the Viceroyalty of Peru, the largest administrative district of the Spanish Empire in South America in the 16th century, and have been popular since, especially the artisanal types.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Alfajor de Trujillo is a type of alfajor from Trujillo.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The *alfajor de Trujillo* has several layers and it can be of different sizes and shapes as round or square.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It is made mainly with products as flour, butter, eggs and milk, filled with milk candy, some pineapple sweet and in some cases peanuts, with cookies within its layers.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The most famous company manufacturing this products in Trujillo is Dulcería Castañeda, which has locations in Trujillo and Lima and has been making them since 1925.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The mass of the alfajor is made of flour, eggs, margarine, salt, and water.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The filling is made with figs, quince, walnuts, blancmange.
[src:aparon/alfajor] It is one of the products presented in the Gastronomic Fair in Trujillo.
[src:aparon/alfajor] Another variant of the alfajor de trujillo is King Kong milk candy, which is made in both Trujillo and Lambayeque.
[src:aparon/alfajor] According to Guinness World Records, the biggest *alfajor* in the world, measuring almost 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in diameter and 80 centimetres (31 in) in height and weighing 464 kilograms (1,023 lb), was made on 11 December 2010 in Minas, Lavalleja Department, Uruguay.
[src:aparon/alfajor] The giant *alfajor* was made to mark the celebration of Uruguay's first National Alfajor Festival.
[src:aparon/alfajor] More than 30 people participated in the preparation of the record-breaking *alfajor*.
[src:aparon/aligue-fried-rice] It is a variant of *sinangag* (garlic fried rice) and is similar to bagoong fried rice, which uses *bagoong* (shrimp paste).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Although paratha is sometimes said to have originated in Punjabi cuisine, it may have evolved from similar flatbreads from regions connected to India via the Silk Road.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Possible origins include the Persian flatbread *waraki* or from breads introduced by Arabs in India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Sanskrit recipes for versions of paratha appeared in the 12th century.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The popularity of paratha increased during the Mughal Empire, which introduced it across the region.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] During the British imperial era, indentured workers from India introduced paratha to Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, and Mauritius.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In India, several versions of paratha were popularised after the 1947 partition.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten as the central component of a meal, with various accompaniments, often including dahi and pickle.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten for any meal; for breakfast, it is commonly paired with tea.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Some types of paratha are made with spiraling layers, such as lachha paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas include aloo paratha, using potatoes; gobhi paratha, using cauliflower; mooli paratha, using radish; methi paratha, using fenugreek leaves, and keema paratha, using minced meat.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is also used for wraps, including the kathi roll and paratha roll.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The word *paratha* is from Hindi, derived from the word *para*, meaning 'layer'.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Indian English, the bread is always referred to by the specific term *paratha*, rather than *bread*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The word for paratha differs across India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Alternative spellings include *parantha*, *prantha*, *parata*, *prata*, and *parotta*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is spelled as *palata* (pronounced [pəlàtà]) in Myanmar and *farata* in Mauritius.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the Gulf countries, as well as in East Africa, the breads referred to as chapati are more similar to a paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Like most Indian breads, paratha is wheat-based and unleavened.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The dough is made of atta (whole wheat flour), water, and salt, which is covered in ghee.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Oil may be used instead of ghee, and white flour (maida) may be used instead of whole wheat; maida is used for more tender, flaky parathas.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Vegetables, herbs, and spices may be added; ajowan is a commonly used spice in plain paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The common wheat, the dominant species of wheat in the northern Indian subcontinent, results in the light, spongy texture of North Indian breads such as paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The flour used in paratha is typically of low extraction, although high-extraction flour is sometimes used.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It may also use resultant atta, the coarse byproduct of sifting atta.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In commercial preparations, potato flakes may be used as a binding agent.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is rolled out with oil or ghee, then folded.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This process of lamination is performed two or more times.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This usually forms a triangle with four to six layers; it may also be folded into a circle or square.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Stuffed versions of paratha are instead made by shaping the dough into balls and placing a filling inside before rolling them out.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be rolled out using a dough sheeting machine that may produce thousands of parathas per hour.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Both plain and stuffed parathas are shallow fried on a tava, a type of iron griddle, until browned, with or without additional ghee.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Sometimes, particularly among street vendors, paratha is fried in a shallow pan filled with oil, thus containing more fat than a paratha cooked on a tava.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be brushed with ghee after serving.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] While frying, paratha forms distinct layers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The lamination of the dough results in a soft, flaky flatbread.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Its lamination process and layered texture are much like a puff pastry, but it does not rise as a puff pastry does.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Frying (rather than baking) results in a slightly crispy outside, and, in the absence of leavening, the formation of steam is responsible for the separation of crust and crumb.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is similar to chapati, with the only difference in physical composition being the use of oil, while paratha also has multiple layers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is slightly thicker and denser, with a more prominent crumb.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The starch properties of the two breads differ as paratha has fat in its crumb as well as fat coverage that causes more thorough heat transfer.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha has starch granules in its crumb that are deformed and shrunken compared to those of chapati.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Gujarati bread thepla resembles a cross between paratha and chapati.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is the same size as chapati; a single paratha weighs about 140 grams (4.9 oz).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Both plain and stuffed parathas are about 15 centimetres (5.9 in) in diameter and 3 mm thick, with plain parathas sometimes ranging to as thin as 2.5 mm.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha has a sturdy texture, enabling it to be served with thick foods.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Stuffed paratha has a softer texture than plain paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is eaten quickly; a study in the journal *Appetite* found that it took about 9 minutes to eat a 250-calorie serving.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] According to a 2020 study in Delhi, the median portion size of paratha is 60 grams, averaging 1 paratha for women and 2 parathas for men.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] According to a 2013 study in the United Kingdom, the mean portion size is 121 grams for children and 100 grams for adults.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha exists in both plain and stuffed varieties.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Dozens of varieties are commonly consumed.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Regional variations differ based on cooking method or filling.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Lachha paratha has circular spiraling layers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] India has two categories of paratha: North Indian paratha, made from atta, and South Indian parotta, made from maida.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Both are similarly flaky and layered, but the South Indian version achieves this texture through repeated stretching and coiling rather than rolling and folding.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Some versions of paratha have spiraling layers, forming a circle or square.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] 'layered paratha') is a kind of North Indian paratha with many circular layers, formed by shaping a circle of dough into a coil before rolling it out again.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It has a crispy texture and is the same size as a regular paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] *Ulte tave ke paratha* is a North Indian paratha cooked on the bottom side of the pan, the same method as roomali roti.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Cornmeal, atta, palm sugar, ajowan, and green chilli are used to make makkai paratha, while ginger and chilli are used for *adraki mirchi paratha*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Sattu, a type of chickpea flour, is used to make sattu paratha, a breakfast dish eaten in Bihar, Jharkhand, and part of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the Eastern Himalayas, the legume gahat is crushed into a paste that is added to paratha dough.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha has been made with atypical ingredients for nutritional value.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] For example, it may be made with mulberry leaves as a nutritional supplement, which also increases shelf stability of the flour.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Other ingredients that may sometimes be used in the dough include amaranth, flaxseed, sorghum flour, and buckwheat flour.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Many varieties of stuffed paratha exist.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The most common is aloo paratha, with a spiced potato filling.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha uses ingredients such as coriander leaf and green chilli and spices such as amchoor and garam masala, and its proportion of dough to filling may vary.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Along with aloo paratha, the stuffed parathas common in Punjabi cuisine are gobhi paratha, with cauliflower, and mooli paratha, with radish.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Keema paratha uses keema (minced meat), such as lamb, while methi paratha uses fenugreek leaves.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Other common fillings include peas (matar), onions, spinach, and paneer.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Aloo palak paratha contains both potatoes and spinach.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Dal paratha is stuffed with cooked dal such as mung beans.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Sweet parathas include *gurh ka paratha* (jaggery paratha).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Anda paratha contains beaten eggs; the paratha may simply be coated in eggs, or it may have a filling of eggs, onions, chilli, coriander seed, and ginger added during frying.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Anda paratha is a common Punjabi breakfast.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Among the Sunni Bohras of Gujarat, egg paratha, known as *baida paratha*, is a festive food.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Punjabi cuisine, stuffed parathas are often prepared from leftovers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] For example, paratha filled with leftover rice dishes is known as *chawal ka paratha*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Bathua paratha has dough mixed with the boiled leaf vegetable bathua and green chilli.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This is eaten as breakfast in winter in North India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha stuffed with besan (chickpea flour) is known as birahi.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A type of paratha from Chhattisgarh uses a dough with wheat flour, rice flour, and leaf vegetables.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Khoa (milk solids) may also be a paratha filling.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Modern variations of paratha use ingredients such as cheese, mushrooms, or soya, and meat fillings are used for some fusion versions of paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The version eaten in the South Indian cuisines of Karnataka and Tamil Nadu is like a chapati made of maida.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] South Indian variations called Malabar parotta and Ceylon parotta resemble lachha paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Malabar parotta, from the cuisine of Kerala, has layers formed by kneading oil into the dough.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Another preparation from Kerala is kothu parotta, a mixture of chopped parotta with other ingredients.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Veechu parotta is a square-shaped parotta eaten in Tamil Nadu.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Ceylon parotta is similar to this, with the addition of a minced meat filling.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Madurai, Tamil Nadu, has a variant called bun parotta, shaped like a bun.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Bidar, Karnataka, is home to the Bidari paratha, distinguished from regular paratha by the addition of a small amount of semolina flour.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Bengali cuisine, the typical paratha—or *porota*—is triangular and usually combines atta and maida.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This is common among both Hindu and Muslim Bengalis.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Circular parathas also exist in the region, with five or six layers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Dhakai paratha is deep-fried and has many layers, with a hollow centre.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Taking its name from Dhaka, Bangladesh, it is also found in Kolkata, India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Mughlai paratha, a dish from Kolkata, which is prepared by folding a paratha over a filling with beaten eggs and chopped onions, sometimes with minced meat.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is one of the more complex forms of stuffed paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Another Bengali version, petai porota (lit.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] 'beaten paratha'), is tossed and torn apart after cooking, resembling kothu parotta.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is a common street food meal, served with ghugni or aloo dum, and is eaten for breakfast.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Some regions of India serve unique forms of paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] 'layered paratha') is a variant in Awadhi cuisine, originating in Lucknow.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is made of white flour and a large amount of ghee, sometimes with sugar and saffron, and it is folded and rolled.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A type of paratha in eastern Uttar Pradesh and Bihar is called *makhuni*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Dulhan paratha, originating from Hyderabad, Pakistan, is named for its elaborate presentation, which is reminiscent of the ornate appearance of a bride (*dulhan* in Urdu); this dish is known for its combination of flavorful ingredients.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Versions of paratha exist beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Caribbean cuisine features parathas that are milk-based and crispy, known as buss-up-shut.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Trinidad and Tobago, this is classified as a roti, distinguished from other rotis by using more oil.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The roti served in Suriname also evolved from paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Malaysian variation, roti canai, is a type of South Indian parotta.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Burmese version, *palata*, may use whole-wheat dough with a filling of peas, served with fried onions on top.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Other Burmese versions include a banana-stuffed version and a pigeon pea-stuffed version known as *bei palata*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Afghan version, known as *naun-i-parauta*, is leavened and cooked on a griddle.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Sri Lankan cuisine, paratha is known as *godamba roti*.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Like other flatbreads in North Indian cuisine, it is served as the central component of a typical meal; the bread is eaten by using the hands to tear the bread and pick up the accompanying food.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A wide range of foods may be served with paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Common accompaniments include curries, sabzi, pickle, and dahi (curd).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Likewise, stuffed parathas such as aloo paratha are commonly served with curd or pickle.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] When served by vendors, paratha often comes with dahi or pickle included.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A paratha may also be served with tea or raita, with which it can be rolled up and dipped.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] As a dessert, paratha may be eaten with brown sugar.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Although rice is the staple in Kashmiri cuisine, parathas paired with kofta are a common dish served to guests.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In middle-class Bangladeshi cuisine, paratha is eaten for breakfast or, less commonly, for dinner, while rice is more common for lunch.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the cuisine of Odisha, it is eaten with egg curry for dinner.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the cuisine of Haryana, it may be eaten with mung beans.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Parotta served with beef is a culturally significant dish in Kerala.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is frequently part of a breakfast in North India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A common breakfast in India and Pakistan consists of paratha, butter, and tea, and it may also be eaten alongside eggs.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Karachi, the phrase "chai-paratha" is synonymous with breakfast, and a 1987 survey found that paratha is the most common breakfast food.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha with pickle and curd is also a common breakfast.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A typical breakfast in Uttar Pradeshi Hindu cuisine may pair paratha with a vegetable dish or sweet halva.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Hyderabadi Muslim cuisine, paratha may be paired with eggs or minced meat for breakfast or with a meat dish for lunch.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas such as aloo paratha, as well as plain parathas, are commonly eaten for breakfast in Punjab and Haryana.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha may be used for wraps, commonly with kebabs.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The kathi roll, originating in Kolkata, is a wrap with a kebab or other toppings served on an egg-covered paratha; This egg-covered paratha in a kathi roll differs from anda paratha, with the egg being scrambled on top of the paratha as it cooks.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Pakistan, particularly in Karachi, a kebab wrapped in paratha is known as a paratha roll.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Lucknow, *ulte tave ke paratha* may be served as a crispy cone, and is the typical pairing with galouti kebab.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The frankie is another wrap using paratha, with various fillings, served as street food in Indian cities.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the United Arab Emirates, paratha is used to make a wrap with potato chips of the brand Chips Oman.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The paratha burger—a hamburger using paratha rather than a hamburger bun—originated in Dubai, at the restaurant Klay by Karak House.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha contains wheat, which provides calories, protein, and minerals and is a major source of carbohydrates.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] As parathas are fried in oil, they have a higher fat content than other flatbreads, The fat content of aloo paratha is about 3.3%, while that of leaf vegetable stuffed parathas has been measured at 5%.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The sodium content may be high, based on the amount of salt added according to consumer preferences.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A 2018 study in Malaysia found high amounts of added sugar in restaurant paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The average commercially produced paratha provides 306 dietary calories per 100 grams.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This portion contains 44.97 g carbohydrates (including 3.41 g sugar), 11.37 g fat (including 5.23 g saturated fat), 6.92 g protein, 3.96 g fibre, and 371.28 mg salt.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A 100 g serving of a homemade paratha—using the recipe published by the Ministry of Health of Oman—has 394 calories and 13.8 g fat.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Parathas have a high trans fat content of about 7.8%.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The fat content of paratha may contribute to a lower glycemic index than other breads.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The aforementioned homemade paratha has a glycemic index of 32, while methi paratha made with curd and oil has a glycemic index of about 60, lower than that of roti.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha contains a high amount of the vitamin retinol, in part due to the use of ghee.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is also high in iron and vitamin A; the use of palm oil has been shown to increase vitamin A content.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha with additional ingredients can be more nutritionally balanced.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Methi paratha is high in fibre and carotenoids, while bathua paratha is especially high in iron and carotene.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The moisture content of paratha is over 40%.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Due to its short cooking time, paratha experiences low loss of moisture and low deterioration of protein.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It loses about 40% of its weight during cooking.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The use of composite flours has been shown to produce acceptable parathas with increased nutrition.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Parathas, including stuffed parathas, are very perishable due to a high moisture content.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Stuffed parathas experience mold growth in twelve to twenty-four hours.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Thermal processing has been shown to increase the shelf life; however, this may result in hardening, discoloration, and loss of shape.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Irradiation has been shown to preserve paratha for over six months.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Other preservation methods include vacuum packing and additives such as sorbic acid.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Historian Pushpesh Pant writes that there is no evidence of paratha in Ancient India, while historian Chitrita Banerji writes that it "has probably been around in some form or another since antiquity." A theory that paratha originated in Punjabi cuisine is commonly held among Punjabis.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Banerji writes that, despite its association with Punjabi and North Indian cuisine, paratha is often said to be related to poli, a flatbread in Maharashtrian and Gujarati cuisine.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] According to Megha Kohli in *The Bloomsbury Handbook of Indian cuisine*, paratha originated in the city of Peshawar (in modern-day northern Pakistan).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Trade routes to India, such as the Silk Road, may have introduced flatbreads from Persia and Central Asia, as well as the scallion pancake of Chinese and Uyghur cuisine, which resemble paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The book *Whose Samosa Is It Anyway?* by Sonal Ved suggests that paratha was adapted from the Persian *waraki*, a milk-based flatbread with separating layers.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A theory supported by Pant states that paratha was invented after the arrival of Arabs in India, who merged flatbreads introduced by the Arabs, like roomali and khamiri roti, with the local puri.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Culinary anthropologist Kurush Dalal stated that South Asian parotta came from Central Asia—through maritime trade routes with the Malabar Coast—rather than from North India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha also entered Sri Lankan cuisine from South India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Recipes for various parathas are mentioned in *Manasollasa*, a 12th-century Sanskrit reference work compiled by Someshvara III, a Western Chalukya king who ruled from present-day Karnataka.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Achaya, the parathas listed in this book were more similar to the modern manda roti.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] These included *purana*, which Achaya describes as the modern-day puran poli, as well as stuffed parathas called *manda*, *vestika*, and *pahalika*, the latter being a sweet version.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Bengal, food historian Jayanta Sengupta attributes the introduction of wheat breads like paratha to the thirteenth-century Turkic conquest.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] During the Islamic era, parathas were common with the Muslim nobility and Hindu aristocracy in Punjab, and paratha was also eaten in the Delhi Sultanate.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The Mughal Empire introduced more complex ingredients to the cuisine of the era, used for foods such as paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Mughal cookbooks included recipes for paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It does not appear in the *Nushka-e-Shahjahani*, from the reign of Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan, indicating that it was not yet present.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Banerji states that the Mughals were introduced to parathas during their conquests of Punjab.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The paratha was popular among Mughal leadership, and it later became popular in Islamic Indian cuisine.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It and other flatbreads spread to Dhaka, in Bengal, during this time.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Sweet parathas were also eaten during the Mughal era.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] People from India were sent as indentured workers to Southeast Asia, Mauritius, the Maldives, and the Caribbean, where they introduced paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] This included the British colony in Trinidad, where Indians sent as workers began using white flour for paratha and other flatbreads as a result of European imports.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] On migrant ships to the Caribbean, cooks began using tavas to make large parathas portioned for several people, originating the variation known as paratha roti.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha was introduced to Malaysia around the 1930s by people from the Indian city of Chennai; the term *roti canai* derives from the city's name.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In 19th-century British India, North Indian snack foods such as paratha were eaten as tiffin snacks as part of an early form of Indian fast food.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A similar flatbread, sheermal, is said to have been created as a type of paratha in Lucknow in the 19th century, although it may have originated in Persia.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Bengal, wheat-based foods such as paratha and luchi were primarily for special occasions (such as Ekadashi) before wheat became a staple food, alongside rice, during the 1943 famine.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] During the 1947 partition of India, Punjabi refugees propagated various stuffed parathas, including aloo, gobhi, mooli, methi, and matar, with paneer and keema stuffed versions appearing later.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Pant writes that tandoor-baked paratha was introduced to India during the partition, out of a desire for roti to be less chewy and cold, and that it originated from Amritsari kulcha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Parathas became a common item at dhaba establishments; Pant writes that roadside dhabas invented lachha and pudina parathas.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Some state that the paratha was popularised in Delhi after the partition.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] However, O'Brien suggests this item was prevalent among Punjabis in Delhi before then, and paratha vendors at the Paranthe Wali Gali claim to have been present since the 1880s.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the Caribbean, paratha was one of several dishes from Mughlai cuisine to be widely popularised in the late 20th century.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The world record for the largest paratha, as recognised by the *Guinness World Records*, was set in February 2024 in Amritsar, when chefs from the Taj Swarna hotel created a methi paratha weighing 35 kilograms (77 lb).
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is one of the most common flatbreads in India—alongside chapati and naan—and is the most common that is shallow-fried.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is associated with North Indian cuisine, in which wheat is the predominant staple and atta is particularly common.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] A 2022 study in the South Indian city of Hyderabad found that the average adult consumes 1 paratha, or 40 grams, per day.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Like chapati and puri, paratha is often homemade, as tavas are a common household item.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Ready-to-eat parathas, sold as a convenience food, are a common product in India, as are several types of frozen stuffed paratha.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Ready-to-cook parathas are sold from brands such as Fingerlix.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is frequently sold by vendors at marketplaces, roadsides, and transit stations, as a consistently affordable meal.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is a typical offering at Punjabi dhabas, a type of establishment on highways.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is served also by vendors next to mosques in North India to break the fast on Eid-al-Fitr; they prepare very large parathas that are sliced and served with halwa.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is less common among chefs, except for unusual stuffed versions, according to food writer Vir Sanghvi.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In North Indian Hindu traditions, paratha is classified as pukka, a type of food that is made with ghee, which is associated with purity, and is served when hosting guests or during festivals.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Historically, orthodox Hindus adhered to a pukka diet; those who wanted to limit oil (for health or financial reasons) would cook paratha like chapati, with only a very thin layer of oil applied using a cloth wrapped around a coin.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Uttarakhand, aloo paratha is seen as an energy booster and, when cooked without oil, a cure for a sore throat.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is commonly included in meals in both Indian and Pakistani Punjab, but it is not as common in Gujarat or in North India east of Kanpur.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha, like many breads eaten in North India, is also eaten in Nepali cuisine.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] According to Banerji, stuffed parathas are associated with North Indian cooking but have spread to every Indian city.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha is served across India between Punjab and Bengal.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] It is also common in parts of Pakistan, except in the highlands.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Mooli paratha is common in North India and Kashmir.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is served by many establishments in Delhi.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] The city has parathas that are baked, then fried, which are large enough to serve multiple people.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Old Delhi houses the Paranthe Wali Gali (lit.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] 'Alley of Paratha Makers'), a small lane primarily dedicated to paratha restaurants, where parathas are always stuffed, using ingredients including tomato, lemon, peppers, and papad inside the parathas.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] They are deep-fried in ghee, more similar to stuffed puri or bedmi than typical parathas.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Dhabas of Haryana on the Grand Trunk Road are famous for their parathas, including Sukhdev Dhaba and Gulshan Dhaba in Murthal.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] These dhabas serve Murthal paratha, a version that is deep-fried.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Agra, Uttar Pradesh, an establishment called Ramababu Paratha Bhandhar serves very large parathas, weighing 35 kilograms.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Mauritius, paratha (Morisyen: *farata*) is eaten across all ethnic groups and is known as a homemade comfort food, particularly as a warm food during rainy weather.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In Myanmar, paratha is served at Indian tea shops.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] People in Myanmar eat it on Martyrs' Day, as it was known to be a favorite food of Aung San, whom the holiday celebrates.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] In the Caribbean, paratha, particularly aloo paratha, is among several Indian fast food dishes in the region.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Paratha is widespread in Yemeni and Omani cuisine.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] People in Oman associate it with Omani–Indian culture rather than a specific region of India.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Many Pakistanis in Norway and in Denmark limit their consumption of parathas upon immigrating, eating it as a special breakfast on weekends rather than daily, in part due to health concerns amid changing lifestyles.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Pakistani migrants to the United Kingdom also eat paratha for breakfast, though some members of the community view it as a holdover from Pakistan.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Among Indians in the United States, store-bought parathas are common due to busy lifestyles.
[src:aparon/aloo-paratha] Aloo paratha is commonly served at South Asian dining establishments in the United Kingdom and Pakistani restaurants in South Africa.
[src:aparon/aparon] It was invented in 1972 by Socorro Vistan Malonzo who learned to bake communion wafers from the Augustinian Sisters of Our Lady of Consolation of the Colegio de Nuestra Señora del Carmen (now La Consolacion University) in Malolos, Bulacan.
[src:aparon/aparon] Her business supplied communion wafers to nearby churches in the province and neighbouring Pampanga as a means of livelihood.
[src:aparon/aparon] She invented the dessert in an effort to make better use of the full communion wafer sheet, instead of having the trimmings disposed of as fish and animal feed.
[src:aparon/aparon] A variant known as **angel cookies** was invented in the mid-1980s by Sister Anesilde Antonio of the Missionary Sisters Servants of the Holy Spirit.
[src:aparon/aparon] While also making use of the excess cuttings of communion wafers, her dessert differs in that the wafers are incorportated into cookie dough in a similar fashion to chocolate chip cookies.
